became his son; and all Balbus' pro- perty, for being ‘sui juris’ he might have property, became the property of Theo- phanes. This was the strict legal conse- quence of Admgafio, though we may as- sume that the Romans had some way of eluding the law. Balbus had a Tusculanum, as we have been told, and consequently pro- perty of his own. Now when Cicero says that Balbus has got nothing by the Adoptio, it is difficult to see what he means, because he could get nothing by Adoptio while his adoptive father was alive. Theophanes could make him a gift.
